external_knowledge:
- Magnetic moment is a measure of the magnetic strength and orientation of a magnet or a particle;
- Melting point is the temperature at which a solid changes to a liquid;
- Electronegativity is the tendency of an atom to attract electrons in a chemical bond;
- Ionization energy is the energy required to remove the most loosely bound electron from a neutral atom in its ground state;
- Covalent radius is half the distance between two atoms of the same element when they are bonded by a single covalent bond;
- Electron affinity is the energy change when an electron is added to a neutral atom to form a negative ion.

sql:
SELECT symbol
FROM elements
WHERE melting_point > (
    SELECT AVG(melting_point)
    FROM elements
);

SELECT COUNT(element_id) AS noble_gas_count
FROM periodic_table_positions
WHERE column = 18;

SELECT symbol
FROM elements
WHERE atomic_weight > (SELECT AVG(atomic_weight) FROM elements);

SELECT AVG(magnetic_moment) AS average_magnetic_moment
FROM magnetic_moments
WHERE magnetic_moment_units = 'Bohr magnetons';

SELECT DISTINCT symbol
FROM elements
WHERE melting_point > 1000;

SELECT MAX(n_valence) AS max_valence
FROM valence_electrons
WHERE ns_valence > 1;

external_knowledge:
- Elements with a column position of 18 in the periodic table are noble gases;
- Noble gases are known for their full valence electron shells, typically having 8 valence electrons, except for helium which has 2;
- Atomic weight is a measure of the average mass of atoms of an element.

